51. We recommended that the MDRRMO coordinate with the Office of Civil Defense (OCD) in preparing and submitting the Municipality’s PSCP pursuant to NDRRMC Memorandum No 33, s. 2018.
52. We further recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
a. To conduct risk assessment;
b. To identify critical processes and functions;
c. To determine scenarios that made disrupt normal operation;
d. To conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
e. To formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed templates and requirements in the PSCP guidebook; and
f. To submit plan to the PDRRMO for review, to the Local Chief Executive for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We recommended:

a. 	That Management create an Inventory Committee for the conduct of physical count and submit to the Audit Team the Reports on the Physical Count not later than January 31 of each year;
b. 		That the Municipal Engineer provide the Accounting Office and the General Service Office with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
c. 		That the General Service Office maintain Property Card for each account and maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map;
d. 		That the Accounting Office maintain Subsidiary Ledger for each account and recognize accurate depreciation and impairment loss for each account; and
e. 	That the Accounting Office and the General Service Office reconcile their records.

a.	We recommended that Management create an Inventory Committee to facilitate reconciliation of records and report;

b.	We recommended that the General Services Office and the Accounting Office update their PC and PPELC, respectively, and coordinate with each other to reconcile their records with the physical inventory report. It is recommended that both offices observe the capitalization threshold;  and,

c.	For PPE items found a station with no assigned value, disposition of non-existing/missing items, we recommended that the Inventory Committee observe the  provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on on-time cleansing of the account.

We recommended to management:

a. 	That the Bids and Awards Committee and the Procurement Unit: a) ascertain the existence of PPMO and APP before proceeding with procurement; and b) observe diligently the procurement process and other rules and regulations affecting it;

b.  That the concerned personnel: a) submit contracts/agreements, proof of registration, result of competition, and accomplishment reports of those paid honorarium; b) submit invitation letter sent to media who were paid honorarium; c) exact refund: c.1) for unutilized balance; c.2) from those who were doubly compensated including the videographers contracted under the trade name CINEMAGIX; d) submit documents relating to observations on meals and snacks, lights, sounds and led wall and distribution list of items; e) submit proof  in connection with observations on signatures in the payrolls and those who received prize but not in the list of participants; and f) submit office order issued to drivers, carpenters, electrician, labor, painter who were paid honorarium and basis of rate;

c.	That the concerned personnel ensure that programs/projects/activities charged to SEF are in the approved budget for a calendar year; and
d. 	That the Special Disbursing Officer submit valid justification in connection with the observations on the deficiencies relative to the first and the revised liquidation.

We recommended:

a. 	That Management strictly follow the set implementing guidelines by DBM and DSWD in granting financial assistance to rightfully applicants following proper procedure and within territorial jurisdiction:
b. 	That the treasurer or concerned personnel submit Affidavit from the claimants that they received the amount indicated in the disbursement voucher;
c. 	That the social welfare worker submit the following:

c.1  Case Study Report for claimants with case study conducted by the CUMC as listed in Table 2;

c.2  Medical prescription and request of medical laboratory tests/procedures to support the claims of individuals named in Table 3;

c.3 Proof of relationship between the claimant and patient/beneficiary as listed in Table 4; and
d. 	Also, we recommended that should there be another tranche of LGSF-FA, consider direct payment scheme of hospital/funeral service bills to the entities concerned. Also, consider integrating the direct payment scheme in Municipality’s Executive Order No. JRTU016, an Executive Order Establishing Policy Guidelines for Provision of Direct Financial and Material Assistance to Individuals/Families and Communities in Crisis or difficult Situation Under the Protective Service Program.

We recommended that Management:

a. Establish the Local Council for the Protection of Children (LCPC) of the Municipality which shall be responsible in the development and implementation of a comprehensive plan on delinquency prevention, and oversight of its proper implementation pursuant to Section 15 of RA 9;

b. Include in the programs, projects and activities of the LCPC government interventions related to juvenile justice and welfare; 

c. Set aside an amount, or partner with private individuals/entities or NGOs licensed and accredited by the DSWD, to establish a Youth Detention Home for the protection and welfare of the children/youth pursuant to Section 49 of RA 9344 and as mandated by the Family Courts Act; and

d. Require the LCPC to prepare an annual accomplishment report to determine the actual delivery of the intended/targeted outputs as identified in the annual budget, and to ensure that programs, projects and activities advocating children’s rights and government interventions related to juvenile justice and welfare as envisioned by RA 9344 are implemented.

We recommended that Management:

a. Revise the Executive Order on the composition of the BAC without identifying the names of the observers as the latter is dependent on the designation/authority given by the head of the duly registered organization; 

b. Enjoin the BAC to issue written invitations/notices to the qualified observers required under Section 13 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 within the timeline required under said Act;

